---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { u } from "../consts";
---
<Base
  title="Authenticity & Honesty — Grimsley Mineral Co."
  description="How we identify, grade, and guarantee every piece. Plain-English definitions of repair, restoration, and treatment, and our money-back promise."
  active=""
>
  <div class="pagehead">
    <div class="inner">
      <div class="crumb"><a href={u("")}>Home</a> / Authenticity &amp; Honesty</div>
      <h1>Authenticity &amp; Honesty</h1>
      <p>We are a family selling from our own collection, so the only thing that keeps this working is trust. Here is exactly how we describe, grade, and stand behind every piece, and the words the trade uses so you know what you are reading.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>Everything is genuine</h2>
    <p class="lead">Every specimen we sell is a real, correctly identified piece. We never sell a replica or a cast as the real thing. If a piece is a reproduction, it is labeled as one and priced as one.</p>
    <p>When we are not fully certain of an identification, we say so right on the piece and hold it below full price until we confirm it. You will see this on anything marked "identified from research and inspection, not lab-confirmed." We would rather under-claim and be right than over-claim and be wrong.</p>

    <h2>The words the trade uses</h2>
    <p>Three words get blurred by less honest sellers. Here is what each one actually means, and how we use them.</p>
    <h3>Repair</h3>
    <p>A repair means a piece broke and was put back together, glued along a clean break with nothing added. Most fossils and many crystals are found in pieces, so a clean repair is normal and does not ruin a specimen. It does affect value, so we disclose it every time.</p>
    <h3>Restoration</h3>
    <p>Restoration means material was added that was not originally there, to fill a gap or rebuild a missing edge. This is a bigger deal than a repair. We disclose it every time, and we tell you roughly how much of the piece is restored.</p>
    <h3>Treatment</h3>
    <p>Treatment means the piece was altered to change its look, like heating amethyst to turn it golden (citrine), dyeing, or stabilizing. A treated piece is still real, but it is not natural, and we label it as treated. We never pass a treated stone off as a natural one. When a piece says "Treatment: None," it is exactly as it came out of the ground.</p>

    <h2>How we check</h2>
    <p>We inspect every piece under magnification and good light before it goes up, looking for repairs, contacts, fills, and any sign of restoration. For anything where the species is not obvious, we compare it against documented specimens and localities rather than guess. Where an ID still is not certain, we tell you and price accordingly.</p>

    <h2>Our guarantee</h2>
    <p>If a piece is ever not what this site says it is, send it back for a full refund, no time limit. On top of that, if you buy online and simply change your mind, you have <b>14 days</b> to return it in the same condition for a refund. You pay return shipping on a change-of-mind return; we pay it if we got something wrong.</p>
    <p>Every piece is packed by hand and shipped insured. Reserve a piece here to hold it for pickup at the Highway 127 Yard Sale, or have it shipped after the show.</p>

    <h3>Certificate of authenticity</h3>
    <p>Every piece ships with an ID card listing its species, locality, size, and any disclosures. If you want a separate signed certificate of authenticity for a specific piece, ask and we will include one. We do not auto-print them for everything, since most people just want the piece and the honest label that comes with it.</p>

    <p style="margin-top:34px;"><a class="btn btn-dark" href={u("minerals")}>Browse the collection</a> <a class="btn btn-ghost" href={u("contact")} style="margin-left:10px;">Ask us anything</a></p>
  </div>
</Base>
